<subsection xml:id="C7.S13.SS4">
<title>Zeros of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.m1">\mathcal{F}\left(z\right)</Math></title>        
  
<para xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="96" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p1.s1">
In consequence of (7.5.5) and (7.5.10), zeros of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p1.m1">\mathcal{F}\left(z\right)</Math> are related to zeros of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p1.m2">\operatorname{erfc}z</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="97" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p1.s2">
Thus if <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p1.m3">z_{n}</Math> is a zero of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p1.m4">\operatorname{erfc}z</Math> (§7.13(ii)), then <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p1.m5">(1+i)z_{n}/\sqrt{\pi}</Math> is a zero of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p1.m6">\mathcal{F}\left(z\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="98" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p2.s1">
For an asymptotic expansion of the zeros of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p2.m1">\int_{0}^{z}\exp\left(\tfrac{1}{2}\pi it^{2}\right)\mathrm{d}t</Math> ( <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p2.m2">=\mathcal{F}\left(0\right)-\mathcal{F}\left(z\right)</Math> <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C7.S13.SS4.p2.m3">=C\left(z\right)+iS\left(z\right)</Math> ) seeTuẑilin (1971).
</sentence>

</para>
 
